🧠 OS Concept 2: IPC Deep Comparison

Earlier you learned IPC basics.

Now compare deeply.

🔹 Pipe

✔ Simple
✔ Related processes

❌ One-directional usually

🔹 Message Queue

✔ Structured communication
✔ Processes independent

❌ Slower than shared memory

🔹 Shared Memory

✔ Fastest
✔ Direct access

❌ Synchronization needed

🧠 Interview Trap

Q: Why shared memory fastest?

👉 No kernel copying during communication.

🔗 Connection

Shared memory often combined with:

👉 semaphores/mutex

🧠 Memory Trick
Shared memory = fastest but risky
⚙️ COA Concept 3: Branch Hazard vs Data Hazard

Very common confusion.

🔹 Data Hazard

Instruction depends on previous result.

Example:

I1: A = B + C
I2: D = A + E

I2 waits.

🔹 Branch Hazard

CPU unsure next instruction after branch.

Example:

if(x > 0)
🧠 Analogy

Data hazard:

Waiting for ingredient.

Branch hazard:

Waiting for decision.

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Which hazard solved using branch prediction?

👉 Branch hazard.

🧠 Memory Trick
Data = dependency
Branch = uncertainty
⚙️ COA Concept 4: Memory-Mapped I/O vs Isolated I/O
🔹 Memory-Mapped I/O

Devices treated like memory addresses.

Same instructions used.

Example
Device address = memory location
🔹 Isolated I/O

Separate instructions for devices.

Separate address space.

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Memory-mapped:

Same road for all traffic.

Isolated:

Separate VIP road.

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Advantage of memory-mapped I/O?

👉 Simpler programming using normal memory instructions.

🧠 Memory Trick
Mapped = treated like memory
Isolated = separate space
